---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="About">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-sm flex flex-col gap-10">

      <!-- Header -->
      <div class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <span class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.08em] opacity-50">About</span>
        <h1 class="m-0 font-sans text-4xl font-extrabold">What is astro-dx?</h1>
      </div>

      <!-- Disclaimer -->
      <div class="surface-theme border-theme rounded-lg border px-4 py-3.5 text-sm leading-7">
        <strong class="text-theme-accent">Community library</strong> —
        astro-dx is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or part of the official Astro project.
      </div>

      <!-- Content -->
      <div class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <p class="m-0 text-[0.9375rem] leading-7 opacity-75">
          Astro is great for content-focused sites with zero JS by default.
          But when you need client-side interactivity across islands,
          the DX gets rough — raw nanostores, manual querySelector, no cleanup, no structure.
        </p>
        <p class="m-0 text-[0.9375rem] leading-7 opacity-75">
          astro-dx brings the patterns Angular developers know —
          signals, computed values, singleton services, declarative DOM bindings —
          to Astro client scripts. No compiler, no framework, just ergonomic TypeScript.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="flex flex-col">
        <and-accordion>
          <and-accordion-item>
            <span slot="header">Why not just use Preact or Vue islands?</span>
            <p slot="content" class="m-0 text-sm leading-7 opacity-65">
              You can — and sometimes you should. astro-dx fills the gap for components
              that need interactivity but not a full framework. Less JS, more native.
            </p>
          </and-accordion-item>
          <and-accordion-item>
            <span slot="header">Why not Alpine.js?</span>
            <p slot="content" class="m-0 text-sm leading-7 opacity-65">
              Alpine uses eval() for HTML expressions. astro-dx keeps all logic
              in TypeScript where you have type safety and editor autocompletion.
            </p>
          </and-accordion-item>
          <and-accordion-item>
            <span slot="header">Does it work with Cloudflare Pages?</span>
            <p slot="content" class="m-0 text-sm leading-7 opacity-65">
              Yes. astro-dx is fully static — no server runtime needed.
              Built specifically with Cloudflare + Astro in mind.
            </p>
          </and-accordion-item>
          <and-accordion-item>
            <span slot="header">Does it support Astro ViewTransitions?</span>
            <p slot="content" class="m-0 text-sm leading-7 opacity-65">
              Yes. Use onPageLoad() and onBeforeSwap() from @astro-dx/core
              to initialize and clean up safely across navigations.
            </p>
          </and-accordion-item>
        </and-accordion>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
